In article <2eubkc$ibe@electra.saaf.se>
pausch@electra.saaf.se (Paul Schlyter) writes:
 
>There's no point in trying to compress encrypted data!  With a good encryption
>algorithm, such as IDEA, encrypted data look more or less like random numbers,
>without any recurring pattern useful for data compression. Therefore,
>doublespace will not be able to compress encrypted data files at all!  Why
>not instead store them on an uncompressed drive?  They won't take up any more
>space there than on the doublespace drive....
 
   You're right, you can't compress encrypted data--you can, however,
compress data before you encrypt it.  That's pretty commonly done, and
there have been a number of articles/papers on how much strength you can
add, etc....
 
>Paul Schlyter, Swedish Amateur Astronomer's Society (SAAF)
